The term "push and pull factors" refers to the motivations that either encourage or discourage a person from beginning their own company. Push factors are those that lead a person to establish their own company, such as unhappiness with their present position or a desire for financial independence. These reasons may motivate an individual to take the risk of going into business for themselves. Pull factors, on the other hand, are those that draw a person to beginning their own company, such as the potential for high profits or the chance to be their own boss. Examples of pull factors are the potential for high profits and the potential for high profits. When beginning a company, it is important to keep in mind the many elements that influence an individual's choice to become an entrepreneur, including both push forces and pull ones. 